e, "mention": "vitellogenin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9767249226570129, "span": {"begin": 993, "end": 1005}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "brown trout primary hepatocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8206173181533813, "span": {"begin": 1019, "end": 1050}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:99804"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "brown trout", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7981479167938232, "span": {"begin": 1019, "end": 1030}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rainbow trout and zebrafish liver cell lines", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7625007629394531, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1099}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:8022"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rainbow trout", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7962799072265625, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1068}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.44737163186073303, "span": {"begin": 1073, "end": 1082}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Nafoxidine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992571473121643, "span": {"begin": 1140, "end": 1150}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009594"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CI-628", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979742169380188, "span": {"begin": 1155, "end": 1161}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992828965187073, "span": {"begin": 1170, "end": 1178}}, {"id": ["mesh:C073189"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "vitellogenin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.5116002559661865, "span": {"begin": 1187, "end": 1199}}], "text": "Eleven ER antagonists were shown to reduce in vitro E2-induced vitellogenin production by rainbow trout hepatocytes in a concentration-dependent manner (Petersen and Tollefsen 2012).  A review by Navas and Segner (Navas and Segner 2006) reports inhibition of E2-induced vitellogenin induction in primary fish liver cells to be useful for detecting anti-estrogens.  Methyl-piperidino-pyrazole (MPP), a synthetic mammalian ER&alpha; antagonist shown to antagonize activation of the tilapia ER, also reduced the ability of estradiol to stimulate vitellogenin production in tilapia injected with the compound in vivo (Davis et al. 2010).  A synthetic musk shown to act as a both a human and rainbow trout ER&alpha; antagonist inhibited E2-induced vitellogenin production in rainbow trout injected with the same compound (Simmons et al. 2010).  Tamoxifen inhibited vitellogenin induction in roach (Rutilus rutilus) liver explants exposed in vitro (Gerbron et al. 2010).  Hydroxytamoxifen inhibited vitellogenin induction in brown trout primary hepatocytes and rainbow trout and zebrafish liver cell lines (Christianson-Heiska and Isomaa 2008).  Nafoxidine and CI-628 inhibit estrogen-induced vitellogenin synthesis in roosters (Gschwendt 1975).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:35:40 +0000 2026"}